SIMPLE: supplication
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Supplication
<hw>Sup`pli*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>supplication</ets>, L. <ets>supplicatio</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of supplicating; humble and earnest prayer, as in
worship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A humble petition; an earnest request; an
entreaty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A religious solemnity
observed in consequence of some military success, and also, in times of
distress and danger, to avert the anger of the gods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Entreaty; petition; solicitation;
craving.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supplicator</ent>⟦br⟧
